-- China shares fall as money diverted for coming IPOs
-- By Grace Li
-- Tue Aug 26, 2014 03:08AM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, Aug 26 (Reuters) - China shares fell on Tuesday, as a batch of initial public offerings (IPOs) that start taking subscriptions later this week divert money from existing stocks.

The Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> closed down 1 percent at 2,207.11 points in its worst day since Aug. 7. The CSI300 <.CSI300> of the leading Shanghai and Shenzhen A-share listings slid 0.8 percent to its lowest close in almost a month. In Shanghai, PetroChina <601857.SS> surrendered Monday's gains with a drop of 0.5 percent. Bank of China <601988.SS> was off 0.7 percent. Growth stocks were hammered including recent outperforming media companies. The ChiNext Composite Index <.CHINEXTC> of startups in mainly nascent industries listed in Shenzhen, which hit a record high on Friday, sank 2.3 percent. Home appliance makers were underperformers. Gree Electric Appliances of Zhuhai <000651.SZ>, Midea Group <000333.SZ> and Qingdao Haier <600690.SS> shed more than 2 percent.